{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3df42544-285f-4ae0-9ad7-34399b61f488","content":"**Not ready to publish.** Here are the issues:\n\n### Blockers\n1. **No template source files** — The directory only contains `.template.config/`. There are no actual project files (`.csproj`, `Program.cs`, etc.) to scaffold.\n2. **`Framework` symbol is inert** — It defines a `choice` parameter but has no `replaces` property, so the selected value won't be substituted into any file (e.g., `<TargetFramework>` in a `.csproj`).\n\n### Recommended fixes\n3. **Missing `$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation/IDE support.\n4. **No `defaultName`** — Without it, `dotnet new mywebapi` with no `-n` flag produces a generic folder name.\n5. **No `preferNameDirectory`** — Should be `true` for project templates.\n6. **No `postActions`** — Consider adding a `dotnet restore` post-action.\n\nThe `identity`, `shortName`, `sourceName`, `author`, `classifications`, and `tags` all look correct. Fix the blockers first — especially adding the actual project content — then it'll be in good shape.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2172ff4e-bc20-456f-98ab-8b8502162ad4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review the template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. Let me check what's required for a proper .NET template.\n\nKey issues I see:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Best practice is to include `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation and IDE support.\n\n2. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Not critical but recommended.\n\n3. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for template packs with multiple templates.\n\n4. **`sourceName` usage** — Looks fine; it will replace \"MyWebApi\" with the user's project name.\n\n\n5. **No `defaultName`** — Users won't have a fallback when they don't specify a project name.\n\n6. **The `Framework` symbol lacks a `replaces` property** — Without it, the framework selection won't actually substitute the target framework in the .csproj file, so the choice won't have any effect.\n\n7. **Missing `postActions`** — While not required, it's commonly used to trigger `dotnet restore` after template generation.\n\n8. **Only `.template.config` exists** — The directory has no actual template source files like `.csproj` or `Program.cs`, which is a critical blocker.\n\nThe most pressing issues are the missing template source files entirely, the absent `$schema`, the `Framework` symbol lacking `replaces`, and the missing `defaultName`. Let me double-check whether there might be hidden files or if the directory listing is incomplete.","outputTokens":793},"id":"b83cc1de-5be2-4893-8247-a691eaa1a387","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:44:45.305Z","parentId":"a5800f91-b6f1-4ac5-a012-98a941223495"}
